Why Git?

A few reasons that well be most interested in to start:

  • Its a great way to safely store organized versions of a project, with a history of changes, off of your local device

  • Its ideal for data science collaborators (including your future self) who need to share & edit code together

  • Built-in tools for project management (project boards, tags, etc.)

Some notes:

Repositories (repos) on GitHub are the same unit as an RStudio Project (i.e.1 repo = 1 R proj) - its a place where you can easily store, access & share materials related to the project youre working on.

When we create a repository in GitHub and have it communicating with a Project in RStudio, then we can get (pull) information from GitHub to RStudio, or push information from RStudio to GitHub where it is safely stored and/or our collaborators can access it. It also keeps a complete history of updated versions that can be accessed/reviewed by you and your collaborators at any time, from anywhere, as long as you have the internet and required access.

A couple of general tips:

  • Pull frequently (if working with anyone else, and when you start working on a project again, even if on the same device)

  • Commit/push in small, meaningful increments and with useful (searchable, descriptive) Commit messages

  • The best way to deal with merge conflicts (more on those later) is to avoid creating merge conflicts. Communicate with collaborators so youre not all working on the same piece of code at the same time.

Crash Course Modules

Setup

Pre-course set up

Students need to make sure they have signed up for a github account which they can do here. Git needs to be installed onto their computers. For Mac users, it should be built in. Windows users will need to download and install beforehand. All users can download up to date verisons of Git here.

A great reference for this step is Happy Git with R. Honestly, if you ever have any questions you should check that link out. All the information we need is and use is contained in there!

Configure Git

First we need Git to know who we are and what Git should call us. Open RStudio, and open the Terminal tab (next to the Console tab).

Run the following commands in the Terminal (type in, then press Enter after each line), replacing the username and email (keep the quotation marks for each) with your username and email used for your GitHub account.

git config --global user.name "Jane Doe"

git config --global user.email "janedoe@example.com"

Next, in the Terminal run the following, carefully checking that the name and email returned match your GitHub information. If your username and email are returned, great! Youve configured git successfully. If not, raise your hand and well help you.

git config --list --global

Basically these steps tell Git please associate me with the github account connected to my email. Also when I make edits or touch things, store my changes as made by username so others can see who made the edits and when.

Store your Github personal access token (PAT)

Once you have git configured successfully in the steps above, install the usethis package in R by running the following in the RStudio Console: install.packages("usethis")

A lot of scary looking red text will show up while this is installing - dont panic. If you get to the end and see something like below (with no error) its installed successfully.

If you cant find the terminal tab, an easy way to get into a shell from RStudio is Tools > Terminal or Tools > Shell.

Run usethis::create_github_token() in the Rstudio Console.

This should automatically take you back to GitHub. Enter your GitHub password when prompted. Youll be taken to a screen that looks like this, with the right options already auto-selected for you:

Change only the expiration date on the token. Never have an unlimited expiration date! These are secure tokens and how you access all your materials. If somehow acquires your token somehow, they could corrupt your data or delete your work. Allowing them to expire keeps your work safe. It is easy to tell R about new tokens. I personally like the 90 days. At the beginning of every quarter its habit to just update my tokens.

Ignore the other stuff for now (you can read about scopes here) and hit the green generate token button.

Copy the generated token to your clipboard

Back in Rstudio, in the Console run the following command gitcreds::gitcreds_set()

This will prompt you to paste the token you just copied from GitHub. Paste the PAT, press Enter. You should see something like this show up if all is well so far (youll have pasted your PAT where mine says REDACTED):

Next run usethis::git_sitrep() in the console. Does it return information about your connected GitHub account that looks something like below? Great! Youve configured git and successfully stored your PAT.

Fork in a Repo

Now lets see if Github is connected and everything worked! Were going to Fork a repo. All forking means is we take a copy of somebody elses repository. We dont have access to change any files on the original repo, but we can make as many changes to our copy and version as we want. This is powerful tool for scientific communication and reproducibility. I can fork into a repo that an author published, check their data and methods, and verify that it indeed produces the results they articulated in their article. Well practice by loading in the repo where this crash course is stored.

  1. Follow this link to the esm-206-github-crash-course repo directory on Github

  2. Click the fork button on the top right. This brings a copy to your github account online

  1. Once you fork it, now you have your own copy of that repo. But you still need to get it talking with RStudio so you can actually work with it. After forking, click on the green Code button, then follow these instructions carefully:

    1. When you click Code, you should see a URL in the drop-down info. That URL is going to be the pathway that github and RStudio use to talk to each other. Copy that link.

    2. Open (or go back to) RStudio. Choose: File > New Project > Version Control > Git, which gets you to a screen like this:

    3. Paste the URL (that you copied from github when you pressed Code) into the Repository URL: section, then

    4. If it didnt already auto-populate, Press TAB to populate the Project directory name: section with the correct (matching) project named linked to the github repo, then

    5. Choose where you want the version controlled project to live on your computer (probably within your ESM 206 folder somewhere)

    6. Press Create Project (optional: select Open in new session if youre already working on stuff that you dont want to close)

    7. What youve just created is a git-enabled project that contains all of the files contained in the forked repo, now sitting right in your working directory waiting for you to work with them.

  2. Lets make some changes to a document

    1. In RStudio, now click on the file test_github.Rmd under the src folder in the Files tab to open it

  3. Go to the Git tab in RStudio (next to the Environment tab). Any updated files/projects will show up in the Git tab in RStudio (probably just the .Rmd this time).

    1. To stage the updated file, select the empty box (under Staged) next to any file that appears there

    2. Commit the staged files by pressing the Commit button, then entering a brief commit message (e.g.testing connection), then press Commit. No error = working. Close that window.

    3. After committing, press the upward green arrow to Push changes back to GitHub. No error = working. You may need to enter your github username/password to do this.

  4. Ensure that you successfully pushed back to github: Go to your GitHub account, and refresh the repo. Do you see recent commits show up? Cool! That means theyve been pushed back successfully. Now, click on the test_github.Rmd file in your GitHub repo to see the code contained does it contain your updates? GREAT. Thats it!

Create individual Repo

Now that your equipped with forking you can be your own content creator! Also youll be working on your own stuff and will create your own directories. The flow is very similar to forking, but I want you to point out a few key differences. Note: There are few ways to do this, but I like to start with github and work from there. If you already made a project locally in R and want to upload it to Github there are ways to do that as well.

  1. Go to github to create a new repository. On your user profile select the repositories tab. The big green button on the top right will say new.

  2. Give a unique name with no spaces or special characters. Typically a descriptive name separated by - is the most common structure.

  3. Select public for now. If you have sensitive data or dont feel ready to publish your results you can always start in private. It is very difficult to go from public to private!

  4. Select add a README and add.gitignore with an R template

    1. READMEs should always be included. They are formated in Markdown (Like this document!) and provide useful descriptions of what the repo does, how it is organized, and who made it.

    2. gitignores are special files that tell git and github which files we should ignore when uploading. For R projects, typically we want to avoid the actual rprojects files and any

    3. Licenses are imporant once you start getting into package development and publishing results. This provides you basic copyright laws to protect your code. For the most part, well never use licenes in this class, but maybe later on youll need to use it and can read out it here

  5. Edit your README to be descriptive

  6. Clone the repo by selecting the green code button at the repo home. Copy the link to your clipboard

  7. Go to RStudio and open a new project.

  8. Select Version Control and then Git.

  9. Copy the url in the first space. Tell R where do you want to store the project locally in the second input line. Keep the same folder name as the github repo!

  10. Make a new markdown document and plot something really quickly using the base mtcars data. Knit the document

    1. Attach palmerpenguins and tidyverse in a hidden code chunk (include=FALSE)

    2. Make a scatterplot of bodymass on the y-axis and flipper length on the x-axis with each species uniquely colored and shaped.

    3. Customize the ggplot into a beautiful image.

  11. Stage, Commit, and Push your changes

  12. Verify on github that your new markdown with changes is included
